AIRPORT VISUAL APPROACH OPERATION ON TRIAL: 1.METEOROLOGICAL CONDITIONS 1.1 CEILING IS NOT LESS THAN 1050M, AND PREVAILING VISIBILITY IS MORE THAN 5KM. 1.2 METEOROLOGICAL CONDITION IN WHICH VISUAL APPROACH CAN BE CONDUCTED BY ATC CLEARANCE: IF THE METEOROLOGICAL CONDITIONS AT ZSHC IS BELOW THE STANDARDS, WHILE THE PILOT REPORTSTHAT THE VISUAL APPROACH AND LANDING CAN BE COMPLETED AT THE INITIAL APPROACH ALTITUDE OR ANY TIME DURING INSTRUMENT APPROACH PROCEDURE. 2. INSTRUCTIONS FOR PILOTS: 2.1 WHEN THE CONDITIONS AT ZSHC MEET THE REQUIREMENTS FOR VISUAL APPROACH, THE PILOTS WILL BE INFORMED BY ATIS OF THE AVAILABLE APPROACH METHODS. TO VECTOR VISUAL APPROACH, RUNWAY 07/25 OR 06/24 IS PRACTICABLE ,OR BOTH PARALLEL RUNWAYS CAN BE USED SIMULTANEOUSLY. THE SHORT FINAL VISUAL APPROACH CAN BE PERFORMED ONLY ON RUNWAYS 24 OR 25. 2.2 THE VISUAL APPROACH CAN BE REQUESTED BY THE PILOT OR INITIATED BY THE CONTROLLER, AND IT CAN ONLY BE CARRIED OUT AFTER MUTUAL AGREEMENT BETWEEN BOTH PARTIES. THE APPROACH CONTROLLER WILL INFORM THE CREW OF THE EXPECTED VISUAL APPROACH, AND IF THE CREW HAS NO OBJECTIONS, IT IS ASSUMED THAT THE CREW HAS ACCEPTED THE VISUAL APPROACH. 2.3 AFTER THE PILOT OF THE AIRCRAFT PERFORMING THE VISUAL APPROACH HAS THE PRECEDING AIRCRAFT OR THE LANDING RUNWAY IN SIGHT, THEY SHOULD REPORT TO THE CONTROLLER AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. THE CONTROLLER WILL ISSUE THE VISUAL APPROACH CLEARANCE AT AN APPROPRIATE TIME. 2.4 AFTER THE PILOT HAS RECEIVED THE VISUAL APPROACH CLEARANCE, THE PILOT IS RESPONSIBLE FOR CONTROLLING THE ALTITUDE AND HEADING, EITHER FLYING TOWARDS THE LANDING AIRPORT OR FOLLOWING THE PRECEDING AIRCRAFT DURING THE VISUAL APPROACH. THE PILOT SHOULD ENSURE THERE IS A SAFE SEPARATION BETWEEN THE AIRCRAFT AND ANY GROUND OBSTACLES. AFTER RECEIVING CLEARANCE FOR A VISUAL APPROACH FOLLOWING THE PRECEDING AIRCRAFT, THE PILOT SHOULD ENSURE THERE IS A SAFE SEPARATION BETWEEN THEIR AIRCRAFT AND THE PRECEDING ONE. WHEN ENTERING AND ALIGNING WITH THE CORRESPONDING RUNWAY ON THE FINAL APPROACH, THE PILOT MUST ACCURATELY MAINTAIN THE FLIGHT PATH TO AVOID DEVIATION THAT COULD AFFECT THE APPROACH OF AIRCRAFT ON ADJACENT RUNWAYS. 2.5 UNLESS THE CONTROLLER HAD ISSUED A SPEED INSTRUCTION, THE PILOT SHOULD CONTROL THE AIRCRAFT'S SPEED AS FOLLOWS: DURING THE VECTOR FOR VISUAL APPROACH, WHEN 8 NAUTICAL MILES FROM THE TOUCHDOWN POINT, THE SPEED SHOULD BE 180 KNOTS; WHEN 6 NAUTICAL MILES FROM THE TOUCHDOWN POINT, THE SPEED SHOULD BE 160 KNOTS. DURING THE SHORT FINAL VISUAL APPROACH, THE PILOT SHOULD MAINTAIN A SPEED NOT LOWER THAN 160 KNOTS WHILE TURNING TO THE BASE. IF THE RELEVANT SPEED CANNOT BE MAINTAINED, THE PILOT SHOULD REPORT TO THE CONTROLLER IN TIME. 3. EMERGENCY HANDLING: 3.1 ABORTING THE VISUAL APPROACH: IF THE AIRCRAFT CANNOT CONTINUE THE APPROACH DUE TO WEATHER, RUNWAY CONDITIONS, OR OTHER FACTORS, THE FOLLOWING PROCEDURES SHOULD BE FOLLOWED: 3.1.1.EASTBOUND OPERATION: VECTOR FOR VISUAL APPROACH ON RUNWAYS 06/07: FOLLOW THE MISSED APPROACH PROCEDURE OF THE ILS/DME Z INSTRUMENT APPROACH. 3.1.2.WESTBOUND OPERATION: VECTOR FOR VISUAL APPROACH ON RUNWAYS 24/25: FOLLOW THE MISSED APPROACH PROCEDURE OF THE ILS/DME Z INSTRUMENT APPROACH. SHORT FINAL VISUAL APPROACH ON RUNWAYS 24/25: BEFORE TURNING TO THE BASE, MAINTAIN THE DOWNWIND COURSE AND CLIMB TO THE DESIGNATED ALTITUDE ACCORDING TO THE CONTROLLER'S INSTRUCTIONS. WHEN THE MINIMUM RADAR VECTORING ALTITUDE(MRVA) IS REACHED OR THE PILOT CAN VISUALLY SEE THE GROUND, THE CONTROLLER CAN VECTOR THE AIRCRAFT TO JOIN THE INSTRUMENT APPROACH.WHEN ON BASE, CLIMB TO THE DESIGNATED ALTITUDE ACCORDING TO THE CONTROLLER'S INSTRUCTIONS, AND TURN ONTO THE FINAL APPROACH FOR THE CORRESPONDING RUNWAY, EXECUTING THE MISSED APPROACH PROCEDURE OF THE ILS/DME Z INSTRUMENT APPROACH, OR THE CONTROLLER MAY VECTOR THE AIRCRAFT FOR ANOTHER APPROACH.DURING THE FINAL APPROACH, FOLLOW THE MISSED APPROACH PROCEDURE OF THE ILS/DME Z INSTRUMENT APPROACH. 3.1.3.DURING THE VISUAL APPROACH, IF THE PILOT LOSES VISUAL REFERENCE (E.G., THE LANDING RUNWAY OR THE PRECEDING AIRCRAFT), THE PILOT SHOULD IMMEDIATELY INFORM THE CONTROLLER OF THE SITUATION AND THEIR INTENTIONS. THE CONTROLLER WILL PROVIDE THE PILOT WITH ASSIST TO ANOTHER VISUAL APPROACH, PRECISION APPROACH, OR A MISSED APPROACH, BASED ON THE PILOT'S INTENTIONS. 3.2 COMMUNICATION FAILURE HANDLING: 3.2.1.IF COMMUNICATION FAILURE OCCURS AFTER THE LANDING CLEARANCE HAS BEEN RECEIVED, THE CREW MAY CONTINUE WITH THE APPROACH AND LANDING. 3.2.2.IF COMMUNICATION FAILURE OCCURS AFTER RECEIVING THE VISUAL APPROACH CLEARANCE, THE CREW MAY CONTINUE WITH THE VISUAL APPROACH AND ATTEMPT TO CONTACT THE RESPECTIVE TOWER FREQUENCY. IF NO LANDING CLEARANCE IS RECEIVED BY THE DECISION ALTITUDE, THE CREW SHOULD JOIN THE ILS/DME Z MISSED APPROACH PROCEDURE FOR THE LANDING RUNWAY. AFTER MISSED APPROACH, THE CREW SHOULD FOLLOW THE GENERAL PROCEDURE FOR AIRCRAFT-GROUND TWO-WAY RADIO COMMUNICATION FAILURE UNDER INSTRUMENT FLIGHT RULES. 3.2.3.IF THE COMMUNICATION FAILURE OCCURS BEFORE THE CONTROLLER ISSUES THE VISUAL APPROACH CLEARANCE, THE CREW SHOULD FOLLOW THE GENERAL PROCEDURE FOR AIRCRAFT-GROUND TWO-WAY RADIO COMMUNICATION FAILURE UNDER INSTRUMENT FLIGHT RULES.
